Well, let's do some examples. I'm pretty good at writing and such, mostly from GMing shitloads of ttrpgs for years, so I'll see if I can help. I apologize in advance for my harshness; I'm autistic as fuck and can only communicate through bitter derision of people who aren't as good as me at things.

>Night light from neon signs pour though your window
First line of the story, and it's nonsensical. What you're trying to convey might be obvious, but you're essentially using a nonsensical device to deliver it. You're trying to say that the room is lit by neon lights from outside, right? Night light immediately makes me thing of the thing children use to sleep better when they're too scared of the dark. I'm assuming the neon signs aren't oppressively bright, and thus that the room is dimly lit. This would set the mood, right? Wrong. You then go on to say that it's 'pouring in', which indicates that there's a large quantity of light that recently started existing which is making the room significantly brighter. Light pours in when you open the curtains on a sunny day, not from neon signs in the dead of night.
Here's how I might have put it.
>You ruminate alone in your sparse room, lights off despite your angry red alarm clock flaring out a time that indicates you should have been asleep hours ago.
>You allow the flickering ambiance of poorly maintained neon signs to illuminate the familiar space, even as they attempt to seduce you into blowing the rest of your meager pay on their promises of a good time.
They're a bit run-on ish, but you get the idea. I've conveyed that the room is spartan (by just saying it's sparse), it's late at night (the alarm clock), you're poor (the room being sparse, leaving the lights off, and letting the neon signs foot your electric bill), and that you live in a bad neighborhood (the signs are flickering and promise a 'good time', a common euphemism for prostitution or strip clubs).
Does that make sense?
